"Not getting a whole lot of good out of this. Very little smell or flavor forme on this one. I had some bigger hopes for it"
"Poured into a The Bruery tulip. Pours a very dark mahogany brown with little light transmission and a half finger khaki head with good retention and lacing. Aroma rich in dark dried and fresh fruit; dates, figs, raisins and plums with sweet candi malt, mildly earthy. Flavor follows, dominated by dates, fresh and dried figs, plums and raisins. Lightly bready, sweet malt. Flavor progresses from dried fruit to brighter fresh fruit notes before leaving a lingering brown sugar and dark fruit aftertaste with a hint of tartness. Medium bodied. A very nicely made, flavorful Belgian, although I found the profile to be closer to a Belgian dark strong ale than a classic quadrupel, although the clove and Belgian spices are faint or absent.  No matter, there is a lot to taste here. Rich and satisfying. ABV is covered well. This may be one of my favorites from the series. A great choice for Christmas."
